    The crash is caused by deleting a pointer value that was not returned by    
    new.                                                                        
                                                                                
    Program state walkthrough:                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int * n = new int(100);                                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This allocates one int on the heap and initializes it to 100.               
                                                                                
    After this line, conceptually:                                              
                                                                                
                                                                                
     n == p   // where p is the address returned by new                         
     *n == 100                                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Then:                                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     n--;                                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This moves the pointer backward by one int.                                 
                                                                                
    Now:                                                                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
     n == p - 1                                                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
    That address does not point to the object allocated by new. It points to    
    memory before the allocation. The original heap pointer p has been lost     
    because n was overwritten.                                                  
                                                                                
    Then:                                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     delete n;                                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This is invalid. delete must be called with either:                         
                                                                                
     1 nullptr, or                                                              
     2 exactly the same pointer value returned by new.                          
                                                                                
    But here n is no longer the allocated pointer. It is p - 1, so the          
    allocator reports:                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
     Deallocation of non-allocated memory                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
    That is the immediate crash.                                                
                                                                                
    There are also later bugs that would occur if execution somehow continued:  
                                                                                
                                                                                
     doSomething(n);                                                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
    would write through n, but n is still invalid because it points before the  
    allocated object.                                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     std::cout << "n = " << *n << std::endl;                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
    would also dereference an invalid pointer.                                  
                                                                                
    Even if the n-- were removed, this would still be wrong:                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     delete n;                                                                  
     doSomething(n);                                                            
     std::cout << *n;                                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
    because then n would be a dangling pointer after delete.                    
                                                                                
    The char * ch allocation is unrelated:                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     char * ch = new char[16];                                                  
     delete [] ch;                                                              
                                                                                
                                                                                
    That part is correctly paired with delete[].                                
                                                                                
    The root defect is that the code mutates an owning pointer with pointer     
    arithmetic and then attempts to delete and use the mutated/dangling         
    pointer.                                                                    
                                                                                
    A minimal local fix for the immediate crash would be to avoid changing n    
    before deleting it:                                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int * n = new int(100);                                                    
     // n--;  // remove this                                                    
     delete n;                                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
    However, that only fixes the deallocation error at line 11. The later use   
    of n would still be a use-after-free.                                       
                                                                                
    A correct version preserving the apparent intended behavior would be:       
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <iostream>                                                        
                                                                                
     void doSomething(int * ptr) {                                              
       *ptr = 0;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
       int * n = new int(100);                                                  
                                                                                
       doSomething(n);                                                          
       std::cout << "n = " << *n << std::endl;                                  
                                                                                
       delete n;                                                                
                                                                                
       char * ch = new char[16];                                                
       delete [] ch;                                                            
                                                                                
       return 0;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    An even better root-cause fix is to avoid manual heap allocation entirely,  
    since this code does not need it:                                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <iostream>                                                        
                                                                                
     void doSomething(int * ptr) {                                              
       *ptr = 0;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
       int n = 100;                                                             
                                                                                
       doSomething(&n);                                                         
       std::cout << "n = " << n << std::endl;                                   
                                                                                
       char ch[16];                                                             
                                                                                
       return 0;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Or, if dynamic allocation is required, use RAII:                            
                                                                                
                                                                                
     #include <iostream>                                                        
     #include <memory>                                                          
                                                                                
     void doSomething(int * ptr) {                                              
       *ptr = 0;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     int main()                                                                 
     {                                                                          
       auto n = std::make_unique<int>(100);                                     
                                                                                
       doSomething(n.get());                                                    
       std::cout << "n = " << *n << std::endl;                                  
                                                                                
       auto ch = std::make_unique<char[]>(16);                                  
                                                                                
       return 0;                                                                
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Use the pointer only while it still points to the allocated object, and     
    delete it only after the final use:                                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int * n = new int(100);                                                    
                                                                                
     doSomething(n);                                                            
     std::cout << "n = " << *n << std::endl;                                    
                                                                                
     delete n;                                                                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
    For the more thorough fix, remove manual ownership entirely:                
                                                                                
                                                                                
     int n = 100;                                                               
     doSomething(&n);                                                           
     std::cout << "n = " << n << std::endl;                                     
                                                                                
                                                                                
